{"text": "was developed by Feynman, and it leads to what is called \"path integral formalism\" - an optional approach to\n\ndo calculations in quantum mechanics. The conventional method is to solve the Schr\u007f odinger's equation with the\n\nappropriate boundary conditions.\n\n226\n\n= = = = = = [45.7] The AB e\u000bect in a two slits geometry\n\nWe can use the path integral point of view in order to analyze the interference in the two slit experiment. A particle\n\nthat passes through two slits, splits into two partial waves that unite at the detector. Each of these partial waves passes\n\na di\u000berent optical path. Hence the probability of reaching the detector, and consequently the measured intensity of\n\nthe beam is\n\nIntensity =\n\n1\u0002eikr1+ 1\u0002eikr2\n\n2\n\n/1 + cos(k(r2\u0000r1)) (45.37)\n\nMarking the length di\u000berence as \u0001 L, and the associated phase di\u000berence as \u0001 \u001e, we rewrite this expression as:\n\nIntensity/1 + cos(\u0001\u001e); (45.38)\n\nChanging the location of the detector results in a change in the phase di\u000berence \u001e. The \"intensity\", or more precisely\n\nthe probability that the particle will reach the detector, as a function of the phase di\u000berence \u001e, is called \"interference\n\npattern\". If we place a solenoid between the slits, then the formula for the phase di\u000berence becomes:\n\n\u0001\u001e=k\u0001L+e\n\n~c\b (45.39)\n\nIf we draw a plot of the \"intensity\" as a function of the \rux we get the same \"interference pattern\".\n\nDetectorSlits Screen\n\nSource\n\nIf we want to\n\nnd the transmission of an Aharonov-Bohm device (a ring with two leads) then we must sum all the\n\npaths going from the\n\nrst lead to the second lead. If we only take into account the two shortest paths (the particle\n\ncan pass through one arm or the other arm), then we get a result that is formally identical to the result for the two\n\nslit geometry. In reality we must take into account all the possible paths. That is a very long calculation, leading to\n\na Fabry-Perrot type result (see previous lecture).", "embedding": [-0.0056878105, -0.016757028, 0.004783161, -0.010485289, -0.058798227, 0.0010181367, -0.04397327, -0.027582599, -0.035838928, 0.09353669, 0.045214992, -0.0045242864, 0.00030592794, -0.009978431, -0.019911695, 0.035496213, 0.005924862, -0.030998178, -0.058267117, 0.03556278, 0.005320903, 0.030727891, -0.054039184, -0.008773871, -0.017320903, 0.04700881, 0.039630134, -0.002431044, 0.008452724, 0.05281465, 0.046403047, -0.027398737, -0.0001592741, -0.0034903942, 0.00326557, -0.017387252, 0.034218002, -0.04473596, 0.01156642, -0.026881091, 0.018359369, 0.02231604, -0.0055730226, -0.059505522, -0.038235176, -0.029219821, -0.007827757, -0.016829772, 0.0007800428, -0.029766226, -0.02064853, 0.0094637545, 0.046152335, -0.036930706, -0.02219021, -0.045720905, 0.0024817465, 0.04002284, -0.026488598, 0.02061251, 0.051129635, 0.0118666375, -0.014870344, -0.02701872, 0.025479559, 0.04971528, -0.035364047, 0.011635438, 0.0104597425, -0.03077778, 0.0077026812, -0.012484319, 0.0068608974, 0.015432141, -0.025131814, 0.024449864, 0.022415016, -0.029105345, -0.021610597, -0.025286425, 0.005612357, -0.04075911, -0.038879145, -0.00049767626, -0.006599026, 0.0070853205, -0.0022454732, -0.003523353, 0.01407356, 0.0015375009, 0.049633674, 0.053526726, 0.0056828125, -0.031214695, 0.025497416, 0.026496828, -0.012564089, 0.027599165, 0.01815736, 0.036807846, 0.012451492, 0.09254547, -0.016070094, 0.057239685, -0.008594943, 0.032839365, -0.003428455, 0.04330029, -0.047547214, -0.07295006, 0.0022750034, -0.014010749, 0.018306717, 0.03172515, 0.0081107225, 0.020731771, 0.008681941, 0.03110278, -0.019563632, -0.029947389, -0.01769848, 0.003946493, 0.053415474, 0.015937636, -0.011993101, 0.01573172, -0.023952883, 0.013889621, -0.04743753, 0.004593817, -0.00083777314, 0.0027739597, -0.0138923535, 0.03043328, -0.02161077, 0.023227422, -0.0031632588, 0.017089617, 0.025942683, 0.